Structure of the dataset¶

This dataset contains 81 columns and 113937 rows. I will extract some key columns for this analysis. Ths most intersting column for me is the APR and what are the important factors for determining the APR of each loan.

ax[3].hist(data=df_sub, x='ProsperScore', bins=ProsperScore_bin);
ax[3].set_xlabel('ProsperScore');
ax[3].set_xticks([0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10])
fig.tight_layout();

CreditGrade: Unimodal distribution with most people towards middle of the credit grade (C).
Term: Most loans are on 36 months term followed by 60 months and least people took out 12 month loan
Borrower APR: Unimodal distribution with most APRs around 0.2, but a significant number of loans with about 0.38 APR.
ProsperScore: Unimodal distribution with most people towards middle of the prosper score spectrum (medium risk).

ListingCategory (numeric): Most loans are for category 1 which is Debt Consolidation followed by category 0 which is 'Not available'
EmploymentStatus: Most people seeking a loan was employed.
EmploymentStatusDuration: People do not tend to stay at their current job for long time.
AvgCreditScore: The average credit score was calculated by averaging CreditScoreRangeLower and CreditScoreRangeUpper. The distribution follows pretty closely with normal distribution which most people has the average credit score of around 680.
StatedMonthlyIncome: Unimodal distribution with median monthly stated income around 3000
LoanOriginalAmount: Unimodal distribution with median loan amount around 5000. Notably, most people apply for loans in "round" number (e.g. 5000, 10000, 15000, etc), so the counts are higher at these bins.

In [21]:
# Function for creating orders to categorical varibles. 
def x_cat_order(order_list, column, data):
    '''order_list -> the list that you wish the order of the variable to be
        column -> string, the categorical column name of interest
        data -> the dataframe of interest'''
    order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=order_list)
    data[column] = data[column].astype(order)

Created a function to avoid repetitive code for sorting x axis variables in charts below.

Average credit score trends positively with prosper score which makes sense, and does not correlate with the term of loans that the borrower applied for.

Key Observations¶

  1. Credit grade, credit score, and prosper score of borrowers follow similar trend of unimodal distribution that most people are in the middle of the scale.
  2. 36 Month loan is the most popular followed by 60 month, and least people take out 12 month loan.
  3. The most popular reason of applying for a loan is for debt consolidation.
  4. Most borrowers are employed.
  5. The most important factors determining the APR of a loan is credit score, prosper score, credit grade, and employment status. If we assume that credit score is an important factor in determining prospoer score and credit grade, APR can be mostly determined from credit score and employment status.
